I had great expectations considering everyone kept saying this was the best restaurant in SF. Honestly, this place is good but it's not amazing. The 90s decor is odd and off-putting. I had the 3 course dinner for $69. The best part of this option is that you can get whatever you want! You can get 3 desserts, 3 appetizers, 3 meat entrees - the possibilities are endless! I had the glazed oysters with caviar, the quail stuffed with foie gras, and the cheese. None of the food stood out, but the service was top notch. Also, a nice touch were the intermezzo small dishes served between entrees. The most memorable part of the meal were the two people sitting next to us. The girl was telling a story about how she had to use Plan B to a man she obviously didn't know very well. TMI.

A great experience eating at this place. I am not sure how to describe the dinner here. The ambiance was just perfect, so was the food. The cheese plate variety was overwhelmingly good, the wine list was good. The food quantity is small of course for a fancy restaurant it is normal, however the quality makes up for the quantity. All I can say is to truly experience and know this place is to eat here.

A special occasion deserves a special place...so we decided to celebrate our friends' destination wedding return at Gary Danko...and this turned out to be an amazing gastronomic night for all! I now understand why Gary Danko is #1. It was PURE PERFECTION! THE FOOD (A+) They welcomed us with two complimentary amuse bouches -- a rich, creamy lobster bisque and salmon & caviar on puff pastry. The tasting menu selection was customizable whereby you can pick from 3-courses, 4-courses or 5-courses from any category. If you are feeling carnivorous, you can choose all your courses from the meat section...and they will portion the size depending on the tasting menus you selected. There are many options to choose from. I chose the 4-course menu with the following dishes: 1) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree - Bar-none this was the most tender and flavorful lobster I've ever had. The potato puree was silky smooth. 2) Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras - Two glazed roasted quails stuffed with foie gras and mushrooms. Rich and complex. 3) Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside - A large selection from all over the world 4) Orange souffle with vanilla, passion fruit sauce and a scoop of raspberry sorbet on top - Warm, fluffy, sweet, tangy. The most HEAVENLY dessert I've ever had! THE AMBIANCE (A+) Warm and unpretentious dining room with large beautiful flower arrangements. We sat at one of the large tables in the back and it was cozy and private. THE SERVICE (A+) Service was impeccable and orchestrated beautifully by the head mastro. Service anywhere else will be sub-par after experiencing this. They graciously offered my newly-wed friends a congratulatory sweets dessert plate and a birthday passion fruit mousse to another friend. SPECTACULAR & BRILLIANT IN EVERY WAY! Tip: Make reservations as early as possible.

One lovely October Friday I was walking up Hyde and passed an open garage door. I didn't think much of it until I was a couple steps past the door and realized that I passed a kitchen with cooks in it! *le gasp* The door to the Gary Danko kitchen was open! I took a couple steps back, made eye contact with one of the cooks, and waved HELLO! I was satisfied with the human connection and was ready to get back on my way up Hyde when the cook motioned for me to come in. WHAT? ME? GO IN TO THE GD KITCHEN? I was like, "Uh is this okay? I'm totally going to cry!" And he was like, "Why?" And I was like, "This is where the magic happens." And he was like, "We're just sous chefs. The magic is upstairs. Wanna go see?" O-M-G. I was totally freaking out (quietly, inside) while he led me up the spiral staircase to the upstairs kitchen. He explained the layout of the kitchen, pointed out the head chef (he waved at me!), and I saw the tiny dessert plates being loaded with tiny cakes! I told him about all the wonderful times I've had at the bar and my favorite tables. It was a magical, surreal experience. I left and was back on the street when Rich ran out and gave me a lady muffin. What a sweetie! FYI - the kitchen is clean and beautiful and smells wonderful.

After hearing all the hype of this place I came in with high expectations, but was reserved because I feel like fine dining in SF is somewhat overrated. This is the 6th Michelin rated restaurant I've been to and I left pleasantly surprised. It was not the best meal I've ever had, however, I felt the service and selection was excellent. I got the 5 course meal for $107 Lobster Risotto - Excellent one of my favorite dishes, creamy rich, good sized bites of seafood - (shrimp, lobster, etc) Sea Bass - I'm not a huge fish guy, but this was by far my favorite dish. It was served over cous cous and had great flavor. The fish was firm when you cut into it but melted in your mouth. (HIGHLY RECOMMEND) Seared Scallops - Pretty standard sear, cooked medium rare to perfection. Only two pieces but with the numerous courses it was nice and light. I probably could have gone with something more unique. Duck - Cooked very well, I'm not a huge duck fan but it tasted more like beef it was so prime and tender. Filet Mignon - By far the biggest disappointment, you can get a much better cut and experience from a legit steakhouse. Pass on this, there are so many other good dishes they have on selection. (The waiter suggested the bison, I should have gone that route or maybe the lamb) I left ridiculously full and with leftovers. It's a great value and I did not leave disappointed like a lot of other highly reviewed restaurants in this tier.

The Risotto and the Scallops. Definitely a MUST get. Least favorite was probably the Bison.     One lovely October Friday I was walking up Hyde and Â passed an open garage door. I didn't think much of it until I was a couple steps past the door and realized that I passed a kitchen with cooks in it!

    Oh my .....

    With close to 3500 reviews, I'm not sure what value I can add to this fine establishments' already stellar reputation, but let's see if I can help anyone out.

    The food: fantastic ! portions are good ( we had the 5 course menu)
    The quality: as expected , also of very high quality
    The service: ahhh yes, PHENOMENAL Â , if anyone were to ask "why would you go to such expensive places?!?!?" All of their questions would be answered here at Gary Dankos.

    The experience, ambience, high quality atmosphere of fine dining coupled with the amazing service lends to a great gastronomic experience. The waiters are all very attentive, our courses flowed appropriately and we were very comfortable throughout our meal. We wish we would've came on empty stomachs but nevertheless everything was very tasty and fresh.

    The tips:
    - Book early and in advance! ! We made our appointment at 9:30pm and didnt get out of there until maybe around 12ish, but our stay was very welcomed. If you wish to have your evenings free, I would make my reservations earlier in the day. They also book up fast , make your reservations with time to spare (within a 2 months time frame)

    - Come hungry! this may have been because we had dinner portions (the big lunch we had didnt help with this either), but my BF has a fairly healthy appetite and with the courses and food parings we had, it even slowed HIM down.

    - Experience the menu! don't be afraid or intimidated to try new things, the waiters are all very open and receptive, and even if you decide to stay on the safe side of the food spectrum you can't go wrong, food just tastes better when its fresh and done right :)
